\newlabel{tab:extraction-crossover}{{IX}{15}{Extraction crossover $K^*$ (minimum rules sharing an $L$-goal body for extraction to lower the bits length) and the marginal saving per additional sharing rule. Clause count accepts at every $K$ ($\Delta =+1$ always)}{table.9}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces The abstraction-maturity threshold for body-pattern extraction (EX30). Cell color is the bits-length change of extracting a body shared by $K$ rules of length $L$: blue where extraction compresses (and the bits gate accepts), red where it does not. The black contour is the break-even ($\Delta =0$) line and stars mark the per-$L$ crossover $K^*$. Clause count accepts every cell ($\Delta =+1$), blind to the surface.}}{15}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:extraction-crossover}{{1}{15}{The abstraction-maturity threshold for body-pattern extraction (EX30). Cell color is the bits-length change of extracting a body shared by $K$ rules of length $L$: blue where extraction compresses (and the bits gate accepts), red where it does not. The black contour is the break-even ($\Delta =0$) line and stars mark the per-$L$ crossover $K^*$. Clause count accepts every cell ($\Delta =+1$), blind to the surface}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Compression predicts generalization (EX38). Each point is one of twenty-two synthetic domains; the horizontal axis is the clause compression a symbolic dream achieves ($1-$ratio), the vertical axis is the mean fraction of held-out generalizations the compressed rules recover, and error bars span five held-out splits. The size-controlled correlation is significant (Pearson $r=0.52$, $p=0.014$).}}{16}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:compression-recall}{{2}{16}{Compression predicts generalization (EX38). Each point is one of twenty-two synthetic domains; the horizontal axis is the clause compression a symbolic dream achieves ($1-$ratio), the vertical axis is the mean fraction of held-out generalizations the compressed rules recover, and error bars span five held-out splits. The size-controlled correlation is significant (Pearson $r=0.52$, $p=0.014$)}{figure.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Open-world recursive discovery closes the partial-closure gap (EX35--37). Fraction of held-out closure pairs recovered as a function of how complete the observed relation is, for three chain lengths. The closed-world exact-match gate (solid) fires only at full completeness; the open-world subset gate (dashed) fires and recovers at every coverage at or above $\tau =0.5$ (vertical line), with zero spurious derivations throughout.}}{16}{figure.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:opi-coverage}{{3}{16}{Open-world recursive discovery closes the partial-closure gap (EX35--37). Fraction of held-out closure pairs recovered as a function of how complete the observed relation is, for three chain lengths. The closed-world exact-match gate (solid) fires only at full completeness; the open-world subset gate (dashed) fires and recovers at every coverage at or above $\tau =0.5$ (vertical line), with zero spurious derivations throughout}{figure.3}{}}
